The majority of the subjects were smokers or former-smokers. There were some differences in the clinical characteristics across the sites including age, lung function and smoking status. nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" aria-hidden="true" data-toggle="tooltip" title="The Genotype-Tissue Expression (GTEx) project was established to characterize genetic effects on the transcriptome across human tissues, and to link these regulatory mechanisms to trait and disease associations. v8 data is based on 17,382 RNA-sequencing samples from 54 tissues of 948 post-mortem donors. Authors comprehensively characterize genetic associations for gene expression and splicing in cis and trans, showing that regulatory associations are found for almost all genes, and describe the underlying molecular mechanisms and their contribution to allelic heterogeneity and pleiotropy of complex traits. Leveraging the large diversity of tissues, they provide insights into the tissue-specificity of genetic effects, and show that cell type composition is a key factor in understanding gene regulatory mechanisms in human tissues.">

nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" title="Context-specific cis- and trans-eQTLs were identified, and cross-population mapping allowed, in some cases, putative functional assignment of candidate causal regulatory variants for disease-associated loci. Authors note an over-representation of T cell–specific eQTLs among susceptibility alleles for autoimmune diseases and of monocyte-specific eQTLs among Alzheimer’s and Parkinson’s disease variants. This polarization implicates specific immune cell types in these diseases and points to the need to identify the cell-autonomous effects of disease susceptibility variants." aria-hidden="true">

nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" title="BLUEPRINT Consortium carried out high-resolution genetic, epigenetic, and transcriptomic profiling in three major human immune cell types (CD14+ monocytes, CD16+ neutrophils, and naive CD4+ T cells) from up to 197 individuals. They assessed, quantitatively, the relative contribution of cis-genetic and epigenetic factors to transcription and evaluated their impact as potential sources of confounding in epigenome-wide association studies. Further, they characterized highly coordinated genetic effects on gene expression, methylation, and histone variation through quantitative trait locus (QTL) mapping and allele-specific (AS) analyses." aria-hidden="true">

nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" title="Authors studied celltype-specific effects of genetic variation on genome-wide gene expression by generating scRNA-seq data of ~25,000 PBMCs from 45 donors of the population-based cohort study Lifelines Deep. After quality control, they first assessed the extent to which previously reported cis-eQTLs from bulk whole blood, using either 94 DeepSAGE samples or 2,116 RNA-seq samples, also show significant effects in the scRNA-seq dataset. For this analysis, they treated the scRNA-seq data as representing bulk PBMCs (by averaging expression levels of all cells per gene per sample, referred to as ‘bulk-like PBMCs’). They detected 50 and 311 significant cis-eQTLs (gene-level FDR of 0.05) that were previously reported in the DeepSAGE and RNA-seq study, respectively. Although only small proportions (8% and 1%, respectively) of previously reported cis-eQTLs were significant in the scRNA-seq analysis, 96% and 90.4% had identical allelic directions as in the DeepSAGE and RNA-seq studies, respectively, indicating that these cis-eQTLs reflect similar regulatory effects. The few discordant eQTLs may reflect the slightly different sample composition of both datasets (PBMCs versus whole blood) and the relatively few sequence reads targeting the 3′-end of genes in the bulk RNA-seq dataset." aria-hidden="true">

nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" title="Authors studied celltype-specific effects of genetic variation on genome-wide gene expression by generating scRNA-seq data of ~25,000 PBMCs from 45 donors of the population-based cohort study Lifelines Deep. After quality control, they first assessed the extent to which previously reported cis-eQTLs from bulk whole blood, using either 94 DeepSAGE samples or 2,116 RNA-seq samples, also show significant effects in the scRNA-seq dataset. For this analysis, they treated the scRNA-seq data as representing bulk PBMCs (by averaging expression levels of all cells per gene per sample, referred to as ‘bulk-like PBMCs’). They detected 50 and 311 significant cis-eQTLs (gene-level FDR of 0.05) that were previously reported in the DeepSAGE and RNA-seq study, respectively. Although only small proportions (8% and 1%, respectively) of previously reported cis-eQTLs were significant in the scRNA-seq analysis, 96% and 90.4% had identical allelic directions as in the DeepSAGE and RNA-seq studies, respectively, indicating that these cis-eQTLs reflect similar regulatory effects. The few discordant eQTLs may reflect the slightly different sample composition of both datasets (PBMCs versus whole blood) and the relatively few sequence reads targeting the 3′-end of genes in the bulk RNA-seq dataset." aria-hidden="true">

nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" aria-hidden="true" data-toggle="tooltip" title="The Genotype-Tissue Expression (GTEx) project was established to characterize genetic effects on the transcriptome across human tissues, and to link these regulatory mechanisms to trait and disease associations. v8 data is based on 17,382 RNA-sequencing samples from 54 tissues of 948 post-mortem donors. Authors comprehensively characterize genetic associations for gene expression and splicing in cis and trans, showing that regulatory associations are found for almost all genes, and describe the underlying molecular mechanisms and their contribution to allelic heterogeneity and pleiotropy of complex traits. Leveraging the large diversity of tissues, they provide insights into the tissue-specificity of genetic effects, and show that cell type composition is a key factor in understanding gene regulatory mechanisms in human tissues.">

nodes.html: <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign" title="Authors studied celltype-specific effects of genetic variation on genome-wide gene expression by generating scRNA-seq data of ~25,000 PBMCs from 45 donors of the population-based cohort study Lifelines Deep. After quality control, they first assessed the extent to which previously reported cis-eQTLs from bulk whole blood, using either 94 DeepSAGE samples or 2,116 RNA-seq samples, also show significant effects in the scRNA-seq dataset. For this analysis, they treated the scRNA-seq data as representing bulk PBMCs (by averaging expression levels of all cells per gene per sample, referred to as ‘bulk-like PBMCs’). They detected 50 and 311 significant cis-eQTLs (gene-level FDR of 0.05) that were previously reported in the DeepSAGE and RNA-seq study, respectively. Although only small proportions (8% and 1%, respectively) of previously reported cis-eQTLs were significant in the scRNA-seq analysis, 96% and 90.4% had identical allelic directions as in the DeepSAGE and RNA-seq studies, respectively, indicating that these cis-eQTLs reflect similar regulatory effects. The few discordant eQTLs may reflect the slightly different sample composition of both datasets (PBMCs versus whole blood) and the relatively few sequence reads targeting the 3′-end of genes in the bulk RNA-seq dataset." aria-hidden="true">
